* SS ''Nebraskan'', built by [[Bremer Vulcan]], [[Bremen-Vegesack]] for [[North German Lloyd]] in 1912 as ''Elsass''.{{sfn|schiffe-maxim.de}}{{sfn|Maritime Administration: ''Nebraskan''}} The ship was seized by the United States on 6 April 1917 at [[Pago Pago, Samoa]] coming under the control of the [[United States Shipping Board]] as ''Appeles'' and then renamed ''Kermit'' in 1920 before acquisition by American-Hawaiian on 5 March 1920 for the price of $538,881.99 and being named ''Nebraskan''.{{sfn|schiffe-maxim.de}}{{sfn|Maritime Administration: ''Nebraskan''}}{{sfn|San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park: Roger D. Lapham photograph collection}} On 9 February 1942 the ship was delivered by American-Hawaiian to the [[War Shipping Administration]] (WSA) for operation under [[United States Army Transportation Corps]] charter with American-Hawaiian as the WSA agent, until title was transferred to WSA on 2 December for delivery of the ship under [[Lend Lease]] to the [[Soviet Union]] where the ship became ''Sukhona'' until return to the WSA on 6 April 1944.{{sfn|Maritime Administration: ''Nebraskan''}} Returned to the ''Nebraskan'' name the ship was allocated to the Army on 17 October 1944 until returned for layup in the Wilmington Reserve Fleet on 17 October 1946.{{sfn|Maritime Administration: ''Nebraskan''}} The ship was used by the Army in the Pacific as a floating mobile warehouse.{{sfn|Maritime Administration: ''Nebraskan''}}
