During [[World War II]], the company operated ships under the War Shipping Administration, some of which were company owned and taken over by WSA as was ''Nebraskan'', and others wartime built and delivered directly to WSA for operation by commercial agents including ''Benjamin Goodhue'', ''[[SS Chanute Victory]]'', ''John Milledge'', ''John Drake Sloat'', and [[USNS Private Leonard C. Brostrom (T-AK-255)|''Marine Eagle'']].{{sfn|MARAD Vessel History Database—Vessel Status Cards}}

In the 1950s, the company ceased sailing operations and was taken over by [[Daniel K. Ludwig]], who used it as a holding company into the 1960s. Ventures at that time included the development of [[Westlake Village, California]].<ref>{{Cite web| last = Watts| first = Ian| title = hawse pipe: American-Hawaiian Steamship Company| work = hawse pipe| accessdate = 2015-03-15| date = 2009-10-23| url = http://hawsepipe.blogspot.com/2009/10/american-hawaiian-steamship-company.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0458-3035| last = COLVIN| first = RICHARD LEE| title = Shipping Magnate Who Created Westlake Dies :  Suburban: Daniel K. Ludwig was 95. In 1967, he began developing the area into one of nation's first instant cities.| work = Los Angeles Times| accessdate = 2015-03-15| date = 1992-08-29| url = http://articles.latimes.com/1992-08-29/local/me-5597_1_westlake-village}}</ref>

