{{Use British English|date=April 2018}}[[File:Astrid Medina.jpg|thumb|Astrid Medina in 2015]] '''Astrid Medina Pereira''' (born 9 January 1977) is a Colombian [[coffee production|coffee producer]] who gained international prominence on winning the Colombian [[Cup of Excellence]] award in 2015.<ref name=ace>{{cite web|url=http://www.ace.sensibledevelopment.co.uk/en/cup-of-excellence/country-programs/colombia-program/2015/1/buenavista-astrid-medina-pereira/coe/|title=2015 Colombia North – Buenavista – Astrid Medina Pereira|publisher=ACE|date=2015|accessdate=10 April 2018 |language=}}</ref><ref name=perga>{{cite web|url=https://www.federaciondecafeteros.org/pergamino-fnc/index.php/comments/astrid_medina_pereira_caficultora_de_planadas_tolima_gana_taza_de_la_excele/|title=Astrid Medina Pereira, caficultora de Planadas Tolima, gana Taza de la Excelencia 2015|publisher=Pergamino|date=March 2015|accessdate=10 April 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref>
==Biography== Born on 9 January 1977 in Gaitania, [[Planadas]], in the Colombian department of [[Tolima Department|Tolima]], Astrid Medina Pereira is the daughter of Aureliano Medina Arce and Rosalba Pereira. She is the fifth in a family of 14 children.<ref name=ace/> Following in the footsteps of her paternal grandfather and her father, who introduced her to coffee farming when she was 14, Medina graduated in agricultural production technology at [[National Service of Learning (Colombia)|Servicio Nacional de Aprendizaje]] (SENA).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/colombia/otras-ciudades/cultivadores-de-cafe-del-tolima-exportan-su-grano-a-nivel-mundial-139594|title=En medio de la guerra, Astrid cultivó un café de talla mundial|author=Ibagué|publisher=''El Tiempo''|date=10 October 2017|accessdate=10 April 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=collab>{{cite web|url=https://www.collaborativecoffeesource.com/the-collaborative-blog/2018/3/13/astrid-medina-en-sus-propias-palabras|title=Astrid Medina en sus propias palabras|publisher=Collaborative Coffee Source|date=13 March 2018|accessdate=10 April 2018|language=Spanish}}</ref>
In 2006, together with three younger siblings, she inherited the Buena Vista farm from her father who had been killed by Marxist rebels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.datamark.com.br/en/news/2017/2/peace-deal-may-help-colombia-to-produce-more-coffee-225318/|title=Peace deal may help Colombia to produce more coffee|author=Willis, Andrew|publisher=Bloomberg|date=14 February 2017|accessdate=10 April 2018 |language=}}</ref> Her mother and one of her brothers had died earlier when they were swept into the river by a landslide near their home.<ref name=bw>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/philippines/business-world/20150430/281694023332524|title=Colombian coffee from former rebel territory stands out at auction|publisher=''Business World''|date=30 April 2015|accessdate=10 April 2018 |language=}}</ref> The farm is now owned by Medina, her husband Raúl Antonio Durán (who also comes from a family of local coffee farmers) and her younger sister.<ref name=ace/><ref name=collab/> At an altitude of over {{Convert|1,800|m|ft}}, it is located in a remote region of southern Tolima which until recently was not popular with coffee buyers as a result of conflicts with guerrillas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hub.cropster.com/store/listings/1589|title=Astrid Medina #10|publisher=Cropster|accessdate=10 April 2018 |language=}}</ref>
In 2014, Medina started to produce speciality coffee under a scheme for developing late-harvest coffee launched by the [[National Federation of Coffee Growers of Colombia|National Federation of Coffee Growers]]. On 13 March 2015, she won the annual Cup of Excellence award for Colombian coffee in a ceremony held in [[Ibagué]], the departmental capital of Tolima.<ref name=perga/> The judges commented on the coffee's "creamy body with sweet and fruity notes".<ref name=bw/> Medina subsequently reported that the award had changed her life, as her speciality coffee sold for over 10 times the normal price of [[Coffea arabica|Arabica]]. The profits have allowed her to improve the farm's infrastructure, to travel abroad and to offer her children a good education.<ref name=collab/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cafedecolombia.com/cci-fnc-es/index.php/comments/caficultora_de_tolima_recibio_en_subasta_coe_10_veces_el_precio_de_mercado_|title=Caficultora de Tolima recibió en subasta CoE 10 veces el precio de mercado por su café|publisher=Café de Colombia|date=April 2015|accessdate=10 April 2018 |language=Spanish}}</ref>
==Family== Medina's husband, Raúl Antonio Duran, graduated as a veterinarian. The couple have a son and daughter.<ref name=collab/>
