{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}} '''Gerardus Jozef Dusseldorp''' {{post-nominals|country=USA-cats|AO}} (2 December 1918{{spaced ndash}}22 April 2000) was a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] [[engineer]] and the founder of [[Civil and Civic]], the financing arm of which later emerged as [[Lend Lease Corporation]], one of [[Australia]]'s largest companies.
==Career== Born in [[Utrecht (city)|Utrecht]] in the [[Netherlands]] in December 1918,<ref name=book>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1YBcy4lR1RwC&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=Dick+Dusseldorp&source=bl&ots=6lhKAlZHXS&sig=eD5AiCs4WEwFFpQjRcy-jF7wo90&hl=en&ei=wP5iSqPhMYWhjAfuwKzxDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=8 Clark, L. Page 18]</ref> Gerardus Dusseldorp was known as ''Dik'' as a child, the [[anglicise]]d version of which stuck with him for the rest of his life.<ref>Clark, L. Page 19</ref> During [[World War II]], as a [[Netherlands|Dutchman]] of working age, he was deported to [[Berlin]], to work as forced labour.<ref name="Clark, L. Page 22">Clark, L. Page 22</ref> Returning to the [[Netherlands]], he secured work with a [[Denmark|Danish]] firm building a railway from [[Copenhagen]] to [[Hamburg]].<ref name="Clark, L. Page 22"/> In late 1943 he was transported to [[Kraków]], again as forced labour but this time for the [[Siemens|Siemens Organisation]].<ref name="Clark, L. Page 22"/> In Summer 1944 he escaped and returned again to the [[Netherlands]].<ref name="Clark, L. Page 22"/>
In 1945 he and his brother Hank secured jobs at ''Bredero's Bouwbedrijf'', a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] housebuilder established in the 1870s.<ref name="Clark, L. Page 24">Clark, L. Page 24</ref> By 1947 he had been promoted to Construction Manager.<ref name="Clark, L. Page 24"/> In March 1951 Bredero's sent him to [[Australia]] to seek out business opportunities: there he established [[Civil and Civic]], the success of which was based on the principle that the designer should be employed by the contractor rather than the other way round.<ref>Clark, L. Page 30</ref> During the 1950s, 1960s and 1970s he undertook residential housing developments such as Harbour Heights Estate and was a competitor of [[Leslie Joseph Hooker]] and [[LJ Hooker|Hooker]]’s housing developments.<ref>[http://www.willoughbydhs.org.au/History/Suburbs/Suburbs-MiddleCove.html Middle Cove]. Willoughby District Historical Society. Retrieved 1 December 2017. </ref><ref>[https://www.houzz.com.au/ideabooks/29267820/list/the-evolution-of-the-1960s-beachcomber-house-to-todays-platform-home The Evolution of the 1960s Beachcomber House to Today's Platform Home]. Houzz. 5 October 2014. Retrieved 1 December 2017.</ref> In 1957 he secured the contract to build the podium for the [[Sydney Opera House]] and, having established his reputation, built the business into an international concern.<ref>Clark, L. Page 31</ref> He went on to establish a financing arm for [[Civil and Civic]]; this emerged as [[Lend Lease Corporation]] of which he was [[Chairman]] for many years.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/money/story/0,26860,24379922-5015795,00.htm Stuart Hornery's illustrious career was shaped by his mentor] Daily Telegraph, 22 September 2008</ref>
He eventually retired from the business in 1988 and in retirement became a significant [[philanthropist]].<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/10/15/1097784025099.html?from=storylhs Rise and shine] Sydney Morning Herald, 16 October 2004 </ref> He was the founder of the ''Dusseldorp Skills Forum'', an organisation that develops and advances the innovative practices of those who engage young Australians in acquiring skills.<ref>[http://www.dsf.org.au/ Dusseldorp Skills Forum]</ref> He died in April 2000.<ref>[http://www.lendlease.com.au/llweb/llc/main.nsf/all/news_20000426 Lend Lease: Death of our Founder]</ref>
==Honours== On Australia Day 1988 he was appointed an Honorary Officer of the [[Order of Australia]].<ref>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=871004&search_type=simple&showInd=true It's an Honour]</ref>
==Family== He was married to Anne and together they went on to have several children.<ref name="Clark, L. Page 22"/> Australian actress [[Marta Dusseldorp]] is his granddaughter.<ref>{{cite news |last=Keenan |first=Catherine |date=16 October 2004 |title=Rise and Shine |url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/10/15/1097784025099.html |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |access-date=19 March 2015}}</ref>
==Legacy== Dusseldorp was the founder of two [[Sydney]] suburbs, one of them being the prestigious [[Middle Cove, New South Wales|Middle Cove]] where the Dusseldorp family lived from 1959 until 2004. The house which Dusseldorp built in [[Middle Cove, New South Wales|Middle Cove]] is one of the top five house designs in Australia: it is based on [[Frank Lloyd Wright]]'s inspirational honeycomb house design and is a good example of [[Organic Architecture]].<ref>[http://www.vanessamcalexander.com/middle-cove-1958.html Heritage Study: The Sydney Suburb of Middlecove 2068]</ref>
