[[File:Karl-Mueller-Portrait.jpg|thumb|Karl Müller (2010)]]
'''Karl Müller''' (born 1952 in [[Roggwil TG]]) is a [[Swiss]] [[engineer]] and [[businessman]]. He is the creator of the Masai Barefoot Technology brand of [[rocker bottom shoe]]s,<ref> {{cite news | title=The Masai Anti-Cellulite Plan | work=[[The New York Times]] | url=http://www.mbt-history.com/history/press_articles/document/152.pdf | last=Grimes|first=William | date = 4 July 2004 | accessdate = 30 March 2011 }}</ref> and holds a patent on his design.<ref> {{cite patent | country=US|number=6341432}}</ref> Müller founded Swiss Masai (now known as Masai Marketing and Trading AG) in 1996 to market his new shoe concept.<ref> {{cite web | url=http://au.mbt.com/Footer/Company/About-Us.aspx?suggest=1&lang=en-AU | title=MBT Antishoe - Company Information }}</ref> In 2007, he left the company on amicable terms and went on to found kybun Corporation in order to market a newer "walk-on-air" shoe concept.<ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.kybun.com/kybun-ag/philosophy/mbt-vs-kyboot.html |title=MBT vs. kyBoot }}</ref>
Products sold by Kybun include shoe models that have a shock-absorbing, adaptive air cushion integrated into the shoe. Kybun further sells an elastic mat, as well as a treadmill that is made with a soft, springy material.
